            <p>Isabela City is the commercial center and capital of the island province of Basilan. The City is located in the northern part of Basilan.</p>
            <p>In the ancient times, Basilan island was called Taguima while Isabela was referred by its ethnic groups (the Yakans, Samal Bangingih, Badjaos, and Tausogs) as Pasangan which the names still hold among the natives. In 1844, the Spaniards occupied Pasangan and in July next year, it was named Isabela, in honor of Queen Isabel II of Spain.</p>
            <p>During the Spanish regime and the American occupation, Basilan was part of a big Zamboanga province, which also included the provinces of Zamboanga del Sur and Zamboanga del Norte. In 1937, the City of Zamboanga brought into existence and made Basilan part of the newly created City.</p>
            <p>On July 1, 1948 with Republic Act No. 288, Basilan island be- came a chartered city, separating it from City of Zamboanga, with three districts, namely – Isabela, Lamitan, and Maluso. Mayor Nicasio Valderoza was the first appointed city mayor who served until December 31, 1953.</p>
            <p>On December 27, 1973, then President Ferdinand E. Marcos issued Presidential Decree No. 356 creating Basilan Province - Basilan as an island province with three municipalities: Lamitan, Maluso and Isabela, the latter being its capital.</p>
            <p>On January 1, 1976, Ricardo G. Mon, then the top councilors of the defunct city of Basilan, officially assumed for mayoralty post as town mayor of Isabela.</p>
            <p>On March 5, 2001 Republic Act No. 9023 converted Isabela into a component city. On April 25, 2001, the Isabeleños ratified the said conversion making Luis R. Biel II as its first local chief executive.</p>
            <p>On August 2001 by virtue of Republic Act 9054 or the Expanded Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM), Basilan became an administrative part of the new region. In a historic move, the Isabeleños opted for No to inclusion in ARMM. The City of Isabela has remained to be part of Region IX (Zambo- anga Peninsula).</p>
            <p>In June 30, 2007, Cherrylyn Santos – Akbar became the first lady mayor in the City. She is determined to make Isabela as the “Promising City of the South” introducing several commitments and reforms to create a promising habitat for the Isabeleños.</p>
